we come up with some really cool
rocket propulsion
ideas gets people thinking.

49:54.825 --> 49:57.127 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: How do we know
it is what
it is?

49:57.161 --> 49:58.929 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
We can't see it from our eyes.

49:58.963 --> 50:02.800 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There's telescopes that see
things, but they
didn't really get a picture of
this planet.

50:02.833 --> 50:05.102 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: It's indirect.

50:05.135 --> 50:09.406 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Imagine driving down a darkened
highway and
a car coming at with its high
beams on.

50:09.440 --> 50:11.542 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You don't know anything about
that car, do
you?

50:11.575 --> 50:17.314 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But there are some ways to kind
of figure
this out using some interesting
technology.

50:17.348 --> 50:24.421 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In this case, what they used was
the slight
wobble that occurs as these two
bodies interact

50:24.455 --> 50:25.823 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
with each other.

50:25.856 --> 50:29.860 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
As the planet orbits around, the
star itself
moves ever so slightly.

50:29.894 --> 50:32.229 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That's enough to infer that its
presence is
there.

50:32.263 --> 50:34.098 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
There are a few other ways to do
it.

50:34.131 --> 50:39.670 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You can actually detect the
slight diminishment
of light as a planet passes in
front of a

50:39.703 --> 50:42.539 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
star and infer that its presence
is there
that way.

50:42.573 --> 50:48.112 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That's how the Kepler space
telescope has
done its work so well over the
years for NASA.

50:48.145 --> 50:51.749 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: So, tell us
what scientists
think they know about this
planet in relation

50:51.782 --> 50:53.117 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
to the Earth.

50:53.150 --> 50:56.720 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Well, I don't
think we want
to live there, Hari.

50:56.754 --> 51:01.325 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's 11 days around its star, so
an 11-day
year.

51:01.358 --> 51:07.665 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It is tidily locked, which means
there is
a light side always and a dark
side always.

51:07.698 --> 51:10.234 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So I suppose the real estate on
the light
side might be better.

51:10.267 --> 51:11.535 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
I don't know.

51:11.568 --> 51:13.570 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
If you're a night owl, maybe you
want to go
to the other side.

51:13.604 --> 51:17.675 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's very close to its star, but
the star
itself is a brown dwarf.

51:17.708 --> 51:19.610 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It's a pretty wimpy star.

51:19.643 --> 51:25.883 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so it can be closer and be
in what scientists
call the Goldilocks zone, the
just-right zone

51:25.916 --> 51:30.387 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
where the temperatures are just
right for
water to exist in liquid form.

51:30.421 --> 51:32.189 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And here's the thing to
remember.

51:32.222 --> 51:36.961 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Wherever we look on this planet,
no matter
where we go, deep down in the
ocean, in acid

51:36.994 --> 51:40.698 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
springs in Yellowstone, if there
is liquid
water, we find life.

51:40.731 --> 51:44.168 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: And so there
could possibly
be -- even under this star's
light, there

51:44.201 --> 51:48.205 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
could be something maybe
subterranean, life
underground, or whatever
constitutes ground

51:48.238 --> 51:49.907 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
on that planet?

51:49.940 --> 51:53.143 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: It will take a
while, maybe
a decade, to kind of figure this
all out,

51:53.177 --> 51:55.779 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
because, again, we haven't seen
it directly.

51:55.813 --> 51:58.349 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And -- but this is something
that has scientists
very intrigued.

51:58.382 --> 52:03.253 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And as technology improves --
and NASA will
be launching another spacecraft
coming up

52:03.287 --> 52:07.491 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in a year or so called TESS that
will be a
little more powerful and will be
looking a

52:07.524 --> 52:12.296 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
little bit closer to us than its
predecessor,
Kepler.

52:12.329 --> 52:17.901 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Possibly, it will solve some of
those questions
for us and determine if, in
fact, there might

52:17.935 --> 52:19.803 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
be life that close to us.

52:19.837 --> 52:23.874 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: And so there
are some projects
kind of at least planned on
getting very,

52:23.907 --> 52:28.245 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
very small sort of sensors or
objects out
farther and farther into space.

52:28.278 --> 52:33.150 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
How could we ever, in our
lifetimes, maybe
not in our lifetime, our
children's lifetimes,

52:33.183 --> 52:34.952 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
reach this to get a look at it?

52:34.985 --> 52:39.289 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Well, we have to
think about
some new ways of doing
propulsion in space.

52:39.323 --> 52:43.260 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Some sort of nuclear option is
what we're
talking about here.

52:43.293 --> 52:48.699 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Once you get into space, if you
can have steady
propulsion that never stops,
fueled by some

52:48.732 --> 52:54.738 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
